Jenkins Declarative Pipeline 
Tasks: Create Jenkinsfile, define build and test stages. 
Outcome: Pipeline execution understanding. 

Aim 
To create and execute a Jenkins Declarative Pipeline by defining build, test, and deploy stages 
in order to understand pipeline-based CI execution. 

Theory  
A Jenkins Declarative Pipeline provides a structured and readable way to define Continuous 
Integration workflows using a Jenkinsfile. 
It divides the build process into stages, allowing Jenkins to execute, monitor, and report each 
step clearly. 
Declarative pipelines simplify automation and improve maintainability compared to freestyle 
jobs. 

Procedure / Steps 
Step 1: Create a New Jenkins Job 
• Create a new item of type Pipeline 
• Pipeline jobs support multi-stage CI workflows. 

Step 2: Add Job Description 
• Enter a brief description of the pipeline job 
• Improves job clarity and documentation. 

Step 3: Discard Old Builds 
• Manages storage by removing outdated pipeline runs. 

Step 4: Define Declarative Pipeline Script 
• Select Pipeline script and enable Groovy Sandbox 
• Define stages: 
o Build 
o Test 
o Deploy 
• Declarative syntax clearly defines CI stages and execution order. 

Step 5: Run the Pipeline 
• Build Now → Triggers pipeline execution. 

Step 6: Verify Console Output 
• Console Output → Messages observes (Building…Testing…Deploying…) 
• Confirms successful stage-wise execution.

